	<tr>
		
			<td colspan="2" bgcolor="#DEDACB" background="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/tb_beige.gif">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				You could sum up this entire post under the following phrase: &quot;Get into a good guild&quot;.<BR>
<BR>
That is what is required for this individual to achive this path. <BR>
<BR>
I see several problems with this guide that leave me with a bit of apprehension:<BR>
<BR>
Most newbies (including myself) have'nt a clue where any of these areas are at. I can remember my first trip to Gfay. I was utterly lost without a guide. Chances are, most newbies would find themselves in the exact same situation. I would guess that either you have been playing EQ for quite some time before building a shaman, or you had a group that helped you out most of the way. <BR>
<BR>
Either of which really couldn't be considered a guide per say. As the events that lead to your success are a rarity. Although, there is merit in the guide, as it did work for you. But may very well fail for others. That is why I am posting an alternative.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
I must admit, Im a level 16 barb-shaman toughing it out in halas.I have had this character all of two weeks and have gotten most of my equipment through outright trade (although some was donated by a kind soul. That happened at level 15). I haven't begged, twinked, or guilded to get where I am. <BR>
<BR>
<BR>
Here is what I did to get to 15 quickly within two weeks.<BR>
<BR>
Levels 1-5: Train your 1HB 5 pts (to start). Go out and kill monsters until you can afford Burst of Flame. Once you have that spell, you can pull monsters individually. Without having to worry about them ganging up on you.<BR>
You should start killing Welps and Decayed skeletons at first. They are the MoB's that give you plain cash. Use all of your cash to buy spells. At level 3, you should start soloing polar bear calves. You may get lucky and loot HQ bear skins. They are worth 30 PP (which is a dream come true at your level). Also,they carry white polar bear skins. Turn these into cindl to get patchwork armor (and exp).<BR>
At level 4, start killing spiders too. They carry fungus, which can be used to get spells through a shaman guild quest.<BR>
At level 5, you should have all of your level 1 spells, and enough cash to buy most of your level 5 spells. Be sure you at least have frost rift.<BR>
Go camp the gnoll guards at the entrance to BB until level 7. At level 7, do the Initiate symbol of the tribunal quest. This requires a run to the qeynos bank. Be sure to get an SoW before attemtping to run through BB. Once you zone in, run through without stopping for anything.<BR>
The initiate symbol allows you to summon a magical hammer. <BR>
Go back to BB and continue hunting gnolls at the entrance. Collect teeth in sets of 3 and turn them in at the warrior guild for experience and gold. You can also solo goblin scouts near bandl at this level. They drop ice goblin beads (another quest item that can be turned in at the warrior guild in sets of 6) and backpacks. <BR>
<BR>
Once you reach 9, buy spells. Be sure to get tainted breath, which can be found on the shaman merchant north of snowflake on the everfrost tundra.<BR>
<BR>
At level 9, find a tank and start hunting snow orc troopers, polar bears, and mammoth calves near bandl. You should be able to SoW your tank for pulls. Safety is just a few short steps away, so if he pulls back too much, you can flee.<BR>
Orc Troopers drop Orc Wrath Wristbands. These can turned in to Cindl (in the kilt shop) in sets of two for rawhide armor. The armor sells for close to a PP per. I would recommend using it though. Also, troopers drop lixt wing stalks, which are worth close to 5 GP per. This is where loot starts to get better and better.<BR>
Mammoth calves drop hides. Which can be turned into the rogue on the second floor of the bank. Turn them in in sets of 4. The reward is exp, and a piece of blackwolf armor (which is rouge only). Either auction the armor or sell it in the shops. I have yet to see a piece that is worth less than 2.5 PP from the shop vendors.<BR>
<BR>
Continue hunting like this until you reach 14. At 14, your group should start hunting around the south tower (and magens tower). There are orc shamans and troopers out here (as well as Ice Bone Skeletons, etc). Shamans and Mountaineers drop bronze weapons. Which are worth at least a PP per. By the time you reach 15, you should be able to SOLO shamans. Hunt these on the eastern wall (near permafrost entrance). They should be white. Use Spirit Strike when fighting them and the spell &quot;endure cold&quot; to help resist their spells. <BR>
<BR>
At least, this is where I am at right now. When I reach 15, I will be leaving the EF plains as there is no longer any good exp for me until I can kill Mammoth cows. I plan to move to North Karana And kill bugs until level 20, then I will return and kill mammoths for their tusks (worth 10 PP per tusk).<BR>
<BR>
There are also a couple more tips I can give.<BR>
<BR>
1. Get Flash of Light. It will save your life and is very effective in combat. The closest place to buy it is in South Qeynos. In the temple of thunder.Use Flash of light combined with Tainted breath and disease to soften some of the more HP intensive monsters (such as calves and mountaineers). It gives you time to Med as well. Also, It builds up divination.<BR>
<BR>
2. Be very conservative with gold. Do not buy weapons or armor from the shops. You can get far better by buying it from the auction line. The best advice I can give is to catch a teleport to Gfay. The closest you can get is BB (butcherblock mountains). Use the spell true north to get a sense of direction when you arrive. Use a map to get to Gfay itself. Expect to be there for a while. The little amount of money that you have saved up is precious. Try to get your moneys worth. Make sure you know the price of an item before bidding on it. There are crooks out there.<BR>
Also, use your lower level to your advantage. This will save you on Tport Costs and the cost of equipment. Others know that you are in need and most do not have a problem with donating. However, DO NOT BEG!!! Even a small offering shows good intent. Begging in gfay will only infuriate other players and they wont help you. Gfay is more or less the &quot;swap meet&quot; of Everquest (at least on my server). <BR>
<BR>
3. Do not use Root to kill with DoT's. Use Flash of Light instead. It is more dangerous, and there is a chance that it will be KS'ed while it is running. However, root doesn't seem to work very well until you get a little higher. Moreso, It costs twice as much mana to cast and it breaks if you hit the monster for too much damage (like with a spirit strike). So basically, at first, Its worthless (but it only costs like 5 gp).<BR>
<BR>
4. Use Inner Fire to heal. You can recast Inner fire. Each casting heals a static 10 HP. This makes the spell one of the most efficient healing spells in the game. At level 16, I can heal half my HP for about one blue bubble of mana. Use it on your tanks too when soloing calves. I was able to heal and buff a level 9 war while he was killing a calf (the calf was yellow). Use Fleeting Fury whenever possible. it is a good str and dex buff and will help train you while meleeing (and your tank too). It only lasts a short while, but it does'nt cost that much mana.<BR>
<BR>
5. Use summon food, summon water, and spirit pouch as much as you can (dont buy food or water). It will build your conjuration skill quickly.<BR>
6. Do not spend any skill points on any of the different spell skills. they will train themselves with use. When buying a new skill, only invest one point to &quot;learn the basics&quot;. Not all skills work this way, but most of the combat/magic oriented skills will train through usage, even if there is only one point in it.<BR>
At the least, you can train spells on yourself. (I did with flash of light, and burst of flame). <BR>
<BR>
Thats it for now. Soon as I reach 25 (which I expect in the next couple weeks) I will post a full 1-25 guide ;).<BR>

